@node introduction "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  AMidi is an AmigaOS device that can play MIDI music on an easily extensible
  number of target devices. So you can choose whether you want to emulate a
  MIDI synthesizer in software, or if you lucky enough to have external MIDI
  hardware, use it and save valuable CPU time.

  It was mainly written to provide MIDI support for games such as Exult, which
  is the first Amiga program to support AMidi, but it may well be used to provide
  music support for webbrowsers or you can use it as a standalone MIDI player
  since the quality of the software driver is superior to all software MIDI
  players currently available for the Amiga.

  Playing MIDI music from an Amiga program, previously considered difficult if
  not almost impossible on the Amiga (Simon the Sorcerer II lacked MIDI support
  for this very reason) is now a breeze. The MIDI support for Exult consists of
  only about 80 lines of program code, most of which were copied-and-pasted from
  an AMidi test source.

  AMidi comes with its own preferences program (requires OS3.5, a configuration
  file with settings suitable for most purposes is included for those without
  OS3.5), as well as the tiny (about 6 kByte) PlayMIDI tool to play MIDI tunes
  from shell or Workbench through AMidi (proper default icons and filetype for
  Workbench/DOpus5 are included). Then, there's the Simon II Jukebox, a tiny
  Shell tool that allows Simon II owners to listen to all 171 (sic!) MIDI tunes
  of the game and hear what you've missed all the time in the game.

    Rüdiger Hanke, September 2001
    tomjoad@muenster.de
    http://www.muenster.de/~tomjoad/

@endnode

@node required "System Requirements"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

  AMidi itself has no fancy system configurations. To use the preferences program,
  however, you need OS 3.5 or higher. Since OS 3.5 costs only about 20 DM/US$ 10
  these days, there's no excuse not to have it.

  The software driver needs

    · PowerPC processor, the faster the better
    · WarpOS v4 or better
    · AHI v4 or better

  The CAMD driver needs

    · a 68020 processor or better with FPU

@endnode

@node trouble "Troubleshooting"

@{b}Troubleshooting@{ub}

  If you have trouble with AMidi, please read this section before contacting me.
  Thank you.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} I want to make the CAMD driver the default driver. I select unit 3 in
     the preferences program and hit "Save" but it doesn't become the default.
  @{b}A:@{ub} The default driver is always unit 0. If you want to change the default
     driver, select unit 0 and click on the CAMD driver in the driver list.
     Voilá.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} The software driver doesn't work. It just doesn't do anything. According
     to SnoopDos the last action is that it's looking for the environment
     variable AMIDI_PATCHPATH. When I start another WarpOS program, it says
     "can't open amidi.device".
  @{b}A:@{ub} This is caused by a cache inconsistence. On some systems WarpOS seems
     to have a flaw and not flush the processor caches when it's told to do
     so. This is definitely a WarpOS problem and I can't do anything about
     it since the cache needs to be flushed but WarpOS just won't do it. I
     had the very same problem with my system back when I installed it. I had
     big problems with mixed binaries such as the OS3.9 picture.datatype and
     the PPC version of AmigaWriter. It's gone since I toyed around with the
     settings, but strangely enough, it disappeared after I set the settings
     back to the values they had had before ...

     There is no cure I can offer for this except to use the software driver from
     the AMidi 1.01 release. The problem should be gone on AmigaOS 4.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} I have installed AMidi as sound support for Exult, but I don't hear
     any music. When I switch screens, though, I hear some music for a second.
  @{b}A:@{ub} This appeared after the internal reorganization of the software driver
     with the update from 1.01 -> 1.05. The only fix I can offer right now if you
     encounter this is that you should raise the CPU load setting in the AHI
     preferences (on the advanced options page). 95% or so should do. I don't
     quite understand why this is the case since the new driver should put less
     load on the system than the old one.

@endnode

@node faq "Frequently Asked Questions"

@{b}Frequently Asked Questions@{ub}

  @{b}Q:@{ub} Could AMidi be used by webbrowsers for supporting the BGSOUND tag?
  @{b}A:@{ub} Of course, AMidi was specifically designed for purposes like that.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} Could AMidi be used for music support in Simon the Sorcerer II?
  @{b}A:@{ub} Yes! Sadly, Paul Burkey did not react to my e-mail. If you want to hear
     music in Simon 2, you should e-mail Paul and ask him, but please be polite.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} How about an 68k version of the Software driver?
  @{b}A:@{ub} No. Lack of CPU power. Not even my 060/50 achieves more than 4 kHz
     without severe skipping, and even then it eats up so much CPU power that it
     leaves no CPU time for other tasks. Even opening Workbench windows is a pain.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} I don't want the GUS patches on my system partition, how do I relocate them?
  @{b}A:@{ub} The installer script allows you to choose a path for the GUS patches
     now if you're installing in advanced mode. If you want to relocate the patches after
     installation, just move the directory with the patches to the desired place and set
     the environment variable AMIDI_PATCHPATH to the new path.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} I want to install another GUS patch set, how do I do this?
  @{b}A:@{ub} First, you should delete the drawer DEVS:AMidi/Patches. Then you also
     should delete the file ENVARC:AMIDI_PATCHPATH if it exists. Then simply rerun the
     installation program and choose a different patch set.

  @{b}Q:@{ub} Will there be a full-featured GUI for playing MIDI files?
  @{b}A:@{ub} Depends on what full-featured means. AMidi offers somewhat limited feedback
     due to its current design as a MIDI support for games etc. It would be possible to
     write a little GUI that allows you building a playlist, starting, stopping and
     pausing the music. Retrieving more information and feedback from MIDI files will
     be implemented in future, but isn't implemented so far.

     Now as for who's going to write that GUI; not me, at least not in the next time.
     Besides, anybody could write one, so if you want to do it, just e-mail me for
     developer information.

@endnode

@node playmidi "PlayMIDI"

@{b}PlayMIDI@{ub}

  PlayMIDI is a little tool for "barebone" playing of MIDI music. It can be used
  from Shell or from Workbench.

  The command line template is as follows:

    PlayMIDI MIDIFILE/A,UNIT/N/K,LOOPS/N/K

    MIDIFILE is the name of the MIDI tune you want to play

    UNIT is the AMidi unit number, 0 by default

    LOOPS plays the file the specified number of times, 1 is the default

  To use PlayMIDI from Workbench, specify it as default tool in the MIDI file's
  icon. The provided default icon for the DefIcons system has this set up already.
  When launched from Workbench, PlayMIDI will place an AppIcon on Workbench which
  you can double-click to stop the music.

  Example:

    PlayMIDI "Ice Cream Man.mid" UNIT 2 LOOPS 2

    plays the MIDI file "Ice Cream Man.mid" two times through AMidi unit 2.

@endnode

@node simonii "Simon II Jukebox"

@{b}Simon II Jukebox@{ub}

The Simon II Jukebox is a little Shell-only tool that allows you to listen to all
171 (sic!) MIDI tunes of Simon the Sorcerer II. This tool is usually not installed,
so you will have to copy it to your harddisk manually if you want to use it.

The command line template is as follows:

  Simon2Jukebox UNIT/K/N,TRACK/K/N,LOOPS/K/N,GAMEPATH

  UNIT is the AMidi unit number, 0 by default

  TRACK is the Simon II track you want to hear (1-171)

  LOOPS plays the file the specified number of times, 1 is the default

  GAMEPATH is the path to your Simon II installation (the path of the executable
           file, not the gamedata drawer). If omitted, the current path will be
           tried first, then the original CD will be requested.

Example:

  Simon2Jukebox UNIT 1 TRACK 42 GAMEPATH dh1:Games/Simon2

  Plays track 42 once through AMidi unit 1, with the game being installed in
  dh1:Games/Simon2. Note that if dh1:Games/Simon2 would be the current path,
  you would not have to specify the GAMEPATH option.

@endnode

@node installation "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

  You should not try to install AMidi manually. Please use the provided installer script.
  @{i}It is recommended not to install in expert mode. The script uses version checking not
  only for the libraries but also for the programs and even language catalogs, so it
  won't overwrite newer files by older ones. If you don't believe me, you can try to
  install AMidi a second time and will notice that no files are being copied.@{ui}

  If you plan to use the software driver, then please download the patch archive you
  want to use from the internet (you'll find the links at http://www.muenster.de/~tomjoad/)
  first and place the archive @{u}(do not unpack it)@{uu} in the drawer this guide and
  the installation script resides in.

  Note that the installer does not install the Simon 2 Jukebox, so you'll have to copy
  it manually to your harddisk if you want to use it.

  The novice mode is certainly the most convenient one since it will do most things
  automatically depending on your system configuration. If it finds more than one set
  of GUS patches, it will select the best one depending on your configuration (free
  hard disk space/RAM), prefering the higher quality sets.

  Installing as average user will offer you to control some settings. The defaults offered
  will be those that would have been selected in novice mode. If an option is switched
  off, chances are it won't run on your system. See help texts for more details if you
  need them.

  If you ever want to uninstall AMidi (why would you want to :-)?) just run the installer
  script again and you'll be given the option to update your current installation or
  remove it from your system if you have chosen average or expert mode. In novice mode,
  it will always try to update the current installation.

  To install another set of patches, you need to uninstall or at least delete the
  drawer DEVS:AMidi/Patches manually.

  Uninstalling in novice mode is not possible, so you have to select average for this.

@endnode

@node drivers "AMidi Drivers"

  @{b}AMidi Drivers@{ub}

  @{b}Software@{ub}

  @{i}Description@{ui}
  The software driver allows you to play MIDI tunes on your Amiga system without the need
  for external hardware. It is based on the gorgeous TiMidity++ 2.10.4, which is probably
  the highest quality software MIDI player on any platform.

  @{i}Requirements@{ui}
  You need a PowerPC processor and WarpOS, as well as a set of GUS patches. Three sets of
  patches freely available from the internet are currently supported:

    @{u}Low Quality:@{uu}
    This set of patches by - err - shom@i.h.kyoto-u.ac.jp takes up only slightly more than
    4 MByte of disk space and is thus a good choice for people who merely want to use AMidi to
    play Exult with music. The quality isn't comparable to the other patch sets, and some
    instruments are mapped to similarly sounding ones so that some tunes may well sound strange.

    @{u}Medium Quality:@{uu}
    The medium quality set was collected by Giorgio Signori from Eric A. Welsh's EAWPatches
    (apparently from an older version) and was distributed through Aminet along with an old version
    of Timidity (which is linked to below). There's some drumbanks and sound effects missing, and
    the settings are not as polished as compared to the high quality set, but it's good for most
    purposes. The set requires 18 MByte of harddisk space.

    @{u}High Quality:@{uu}
    This is the fabulous set of patches collected by Eric A. Welsh (EAWPatches). This is
    the only set that comes with full drum and sound fx banks. They take up 35 MByte of disk
    space but deliver an outstanding performance and enable you to hear what the software
    driver can really do. 35 MByte may sound a lot, but remember that AMidi is a shared system
    resource. If you're a MIDI geek, you can't afford not to choose these anyway.


  @{b}CAMD@{ub}

  @{i}Description@{ui}
  The CAMD driver was based on Christian Buchner's extension of Commodore's original
  example source code for playing MIDI files through CAMD. With this driver you can playback
  on any MIDI device accessible through CAMD, such as external MIDI synthesizers. 68k users
  who cannot use the software driver can install GMPlay 1.3 and the software synthesizer
  from the CAMD Toolkit (both available on Aminet) which has been tested and works fine.

  @{i}Requirements@{ui}
  An 68k processor with FPU is enough to use this driver. If you don't have external
  MIDI hardware, you also need the two programs mentioned above from Aminet.

@endnode

@node configuration "Configuration"

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

@{b}AmigaOS 3.1 and earlier@{ub}
  You won't be able to use the preferences program since it's using ReAction,
  so you must use the preconfigured default units. Those are:

  Unit 0 (AHI high quality):   software, AHI unit 0, 44 kHz 16 bit stereo
  Unit 1 (AHI medium quality): software, AHI unit 0, 22 kHz 16 bit stereo
  Unit 2 (AHI low quality):    software, AHI unit 0, 11 kHz 16 bit mono
  Unit 3 (CAMD):               Sends Midi data through CAMD to out.0

@{b}AmigaOS 3.5 and later@{ub}
  The preferences program will be installed to SYS:Prefs. You can start it
  by double-clicking the AMidi icon from Workbench.

  @{i}Unit:@{ui}      selects the unit you want to configure. AMidi offers you
             five units.
  @{i}Unit name:@{ui} you can enter a name for the unit here. Application can choose
             to give you a unit name to choose from rather than the unit number.
             The Exult preferences program makes use of this feature.

  @{u}Software driver settings:@{uu}
  @{i}AHI unit:@{ui}  music is played back through AHI. Choose here an AHI unit
             on which to play.
  @{i}Frequency:@{ui} select the frequency to render the sound data in; for frequencies
             not in the list select "custom" and enter the desired frequency
             below.
  @{i}Format:@{ui}    allows you to select between mono and stereo and 8 bit and 16 bit
             sound data.
  @{i}Volume:@{ui}    this setting is independent of the AHI volume setting.

  @{u}CAMD driver settings:@{uu}
  @{i}Link name:@{ui} enter the CAMD link to which the midi data is sent. out.0 is
             usually the serial port. out.0 is also used to send the data
             to GMPlay 1.3 if you have the software synthesizer from the CAMD
             toolkit installed.
  @{i}Initialization:@{ui} which initialization to send to the MIDI hardware.

@endnode

@node credits "Credits"

@{b}Credits and Legal Stuff @{ub}

  amidi.device, the preferences program, the driver interface and driver adaptions
  were written and are copyright ©2001 by Rüdiger Hanke <tomjoad@muenster.de>.

  amidi.device is freeware. You may copy it as you like, provided you keep the
  archive contents intact and do not remove these credit notices. You may even
  include it in commercial distributions using AMidi.device.

  The software driver is based on TiMidity++ 2.10.4 which was written by
  Masanao Izumo <mo@goice.co.jp>, based on the original version created
  1995 by Tuukka Toivonen.

  The CAMD driver is based on Christian Buchner's improvements of Commodore's
  original source code examples on how to play MIDI tunes through CAMD.

  The high quality patch set was collected and its configuration written by
  Eric A. Welsh. The patches are mostly freeware, except the analog drumset,
  drumset 25 and the patches pistol.pat, pistol2.pat and machgun1.pat. Those
  may be distributed freely but may not be included with commercial work.

  The medium quality patch set was also collected by Eric A. Welsh and was
  put together and distributed on Aminet by Giorgio Signori.

  The low quality patch set was collected by shom@i.h.kyoto-u.ac.jp.

